{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "Clark1977AnelasticSystem",
        "description": "Complete 3D anelastic atmospheric dynamics system in terrain-following coordinates from Clark (1977), 'A Small-Scale Dynamic Model Using a Terrain-Following Coordinate Transformation', Journal of Computational Physics 24, 186-215. The full nonlinear Clark (1977) model assembled as a hierarchical composition of eight subsystems: the isentropic base state (Eqs. 2.6-2.9), Witch-of-Agnesi mountain topography (Eq. 7.1), the terrain-following coordinate transformation (Eqs. 2.20-2.27), the Smagorinsky turbulence closure (Eqs. 2.15-2.19), the anelastic momentum residuals (Eqs. 2.1-2.3), anelastic mass continuity (Eq. 2.4), anelastic thermodynamics with turbulent heat flux (Eq. 2.14) and the diagnostic pressure equation (Section 4). Migrated from AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391 src/clark1977.jl:582 (`Clark1977AnelasticSystem` @component) — a pure subsystem composition (`System(Equation[], t; systems=[...])`, no coupling equations): the eight subsystems are inlined verbatim under `subsystems` (ESS spec §4.7) and remain dynamically independent. Purely algebraic — every subsystem is a diagnostic (observed-only) system with no time derivative. SI units throughout.",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_dynamics",
            "mountain-wave",
            "anelastic",
            "clark-1977",
            "terrain-following",
            "coupled-subsystems",
            "algebraic-system"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDynamics.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-36nh)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Clark, T. L. (1977). A Small-Scale Dynamic Model Using a Terrain-Following Coordinate Transformation. Journal of Computational Physics, 24(2), 186-215."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "Clark1977AnelasticSystem": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Clark, T. L. (1977). A Small-Scale Dynamic Model Using a Terrain-Following Coordinate Transformation. Journal of Computational Physics, 24(2), 186-215 — the complete anelastic system, Sections 2-4.",
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc3918e1eef2c2ee6d8fa8dd73c8f13a85a47:src/clark1977.jl:582\n\nUpstream `Clark1977AnelasticSystem` is an MTK `@component` that composes the eight Clark (1977) subsystems into one hierarchical model via `System(Equation[], t; systems = [base_state, topography, transform, turbulence, momentum, mass_continuity, thermodynamics, pressure_diag], name, checks = false)`. The equation list is empty (`eqs = Equation[]`) — the upstream docstring states 'No additional equations needed - this is a composition of subsystems'. The eight subsystems are assembled under one parent but left dynamically independent: there are no coupling equations, no `connect`s and no shared variables (base_state's ρ̄ output is not wired into momentum's ρ̄ input, topography's z_s is not wired into transform's z_s input, etc.). The composition is purely structural.\n\nMigration approach (ESS spec §4.7 subsystem composition): each of the eight subsystems is inlined under `subsystems`, keyed by its upstream `@named` name — base_state, topography, transform, turbulence, momentum, mass_continuity, thermodynamics, pressure_diag. Seven are copied verbatim (variables + equations) from their already-migrated standalone `.esm` files in this same directory: topography ← witch_of_agnesi.esm, transform ← terrain_following.esm, turbulence ← smagorinsky.esm, momentum ← anelastic_momentum.esm, mass_continuity ← anelastic_mass.esm, thermodynamics ← anelastic_thermo.esm, pressure_diag ← diagnostic_pressure.esm. The eighth, base_state, is migrated here directly from src/clark1977.jl:49 (`IsentropicBaseState` @component) because its standalone target isentropic_base_state.esm is not yet present on `main`; the inline copy is self-contained and faithful to the upstream @component.\n\nNo input re-typing: because the parent declares no coupling equations, every subsystem input keeps the `parameter` type it carries in its standalone `.esm` file. (Contrast the sibling subsystem-composed migration components/gaschem/combined/tropospheric_chemistry.esm, where subsystem inputs are re-typed `parameter`→`state` because the parent's coupling equations `<sub>.<input> ~ <input>` govern them and a `parameter` cannot be an equation LHS. Clark1977AnelasticSystem has no such equations, so no re-typing is needed — the precedent here is components/gaschem/radiation/radiation_fundamentals.esm, which likewise composes subsystems with empty top-level `variables`/`equations`.) The top-level model therefore has `variables: {}` and `equations: []`.\n\nbase_state derived constants: IsentropicBaseState declares five MTK `@constants` (g, R_d, c_p, inv_kappa, inv_kappa_m1). The .esm schema has no constant variable type, so each is carried as a fixed-default `parameter`. inv_kappa and inv_kappa_m1 are derived constants — their upstream defaults are expressions of the others (inv_kappa = c_p/R_d, inv_kappa_m1 = c_p/R_d − 1) — and the `default` field carries the evaluated IEEE-754 double (1004/287 = 3.4982578397212545 and 3.4982578397212545 − 1 = 2.4982578397212545); the derived constant is kept as a named symbol in the p_bar / ρ_bar equations rather than inlined, matching the upstream `System(eqs,t)`. base_state's three `@parameters` (Θ, P_0, z) become `parameter` and its four `@variables` (T_bar, p_bar, ρ_bar, H_s) become `state`; each state is the LHS of one non-differential equation. base_state is dimensionally consistent and is constructed without `checks=false` upstream.\n\nchecks=false: the upstream `Clark1977AnelasticSystem` (and its DiagnosticPressure subsystem) pass `checks=false` to `System` due to unit complexities in the diagnostic-pressure formulation. The .esm schema has no `checks` field and the ESS runners perform no dimensional analysis, so `checks=false` carries over with nothing to encode — the pressure_diag subsystem is copied verbatim from the gate-passing diagnostic_pressure.esm.\n\nsystem_kind: every one of the eight subsystems is purely algebraic (every equation is an `~` relation; there is no `D(·)` time derivative anywhere), so the flattened composed model is a fully-algebraic diagnostic system. `system_kind` is left unset, matching all eight standalone subsystem files and the sibling subsystem-composed radiation_fundamentals.esm.\n\nExamples: this file declares no `examples` block. The example-plot renderer (tools/render_example_plots.py) resolves algebraic (non-dynamic) models with an equation-resolution plan that operates on the top-level model alone and does not descend into `subsystems`; a subsystem-composed algebraic model is therefore not plottable by the renderer. This mirrors the two sibling subsystem-composed migrations radiation_fundamentals.esm and tropospheric_chemistry.esm, which likewise declare no examples. The inline `tests` block provides the full numeric verification.\n\nTolerance (model-level rel=1e-6, abs=1e-9): the flattened system is eight independent algebraic blocks of small closed-form expression trees; the canonical runner resolves each without iterative error accumulation. rel=1e-6 covers float64 round-off and any sub-ULP difference between the Julia walker and the Python gate; abs=1e-9 gates the many intended exact zeros — the residual-type outputs of turbulence, momentum, mass_continuity, thermodynamics and pressure_diag vanish identically under the quiescent default state. This rel/abs pair is the one used by the standalone anelastic_momentum.esm / diagnostic_pressure.esm / smagorinsky.esm / terrain_following.esm / witch_of_agnesi.esm subsystem files.\n\nTest reproduction: the upstream Julia suite (test/clark1977_test.jl:246-260) contains a single Clark1977AnelasticSystem testitem — `Clark1977AnelasticSystem Structure` — which asserts only that the composed object is a `System` and that all eight subsystems are present by name; it makes no numerical assertion. The ten inline tests reproduce that structural intent through the dot-namespaced flattened system and add full numeric coverage: `composed_default_canonical_all_subsystems` exercises every output of all eight subsystems at default parameters (proving all eight are present and computing); eight per-subsystem tests (base_state_elevated_z1000, topography_half_width, transform_full, turbulence_full_deformation, momentum_full_residual, mass_continuity_all_outputs, thermodynamics_all_heat_flux, pressure_diag_full) drive each subsystem with a non-trivial parameter set routed through the composition via dot-namespaced `parameter_overrides`, with expected values taken from the corresponding standalone file's gate-verified tests (base_state's from the closed-form Clark 1977 Eqs. 2.6-2.9); and `namespace_isolation_independent_subsystems` overrides parameters in two subsystems at once and asserts a third, un-overridden subsystem stays at its default — confirming the subsystems are dynamically independent, as the upstream empty-coupling composition requires. All expected values are the canonical ESS Python runner output of the composed model (tools/run_esm_inline_tests.py). SI units throughout."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-06,
                "abs": 1e-09
            },
            "variables": {},
            "equations": [],
            "subsystems": {
                "base_state": {
                    "variables": {
                        "g": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m/s^2",
                            "default": 9.81,
                            "description": "Gravitational acceleration. Upstream MTK `@constants`; enters the isentropic scale height H_s = c_p·Θ/g."
                        },
                        "R_d": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "J/(kg*K)",
                            "default": 287.0,
                            "description": "Dry-air gas constant. Upstream MTK `@constants`; enters the base-state density ρ̄ = P_0/(R_d·Θ)·(1 − z/H_s)^(C_p/R_d − 1) (Eq. 2.9)."
                        },
                        "c_p": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "J/(kg*K)",
                            "default": 1004.0,
                            "description": "Specific heat of dry air at constant pressure. Upstream MTK `@constants`; enters the isentropic scale height H_s = c_p·Θ/g."
                        },
                        "inv_kappa": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 3.4982578397212545,
                            "description": "Pressure-profile exponent C_p/R_d = 1/κ (dimensionless). A derived upstream MTK `@constants` (inv_kappa = c_p/R_d); carried as a parameter with the evaluated default 1004/287 = 3.4982578397212545. Exponent of the base-state pressure profile (Eq. 2.8)."
                        },
                        "inv_kappa_m1": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 2.4982578397212545,
                            "description": "Density-profile exponent C_p/R_d − 1 (dimensionless). A derived upstream MTK `@constants` (inv_kappa_m1 = c_p/R_d − 1); carried as a parameter with the evaluated default 1004/287 − 1 = 2.4982578397212545. Exponent of the base-state density profile (Eq. 2.9)."
                        },
                        "Θ": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "K",
                            "default": 300.0,
                            "description": "Reference (constant) potential temperature of the isentropic base state — Clark (1977) Eq. 2.6 assumes θ̄(z) = Θ throughout the column."
                        },
                        "P_0": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "Pa",
                            "default": 100000.0,
                            "description": "Surface pressure — the base-state pressure p̄ at z = 0."
                        },
                        "z": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m",
                            "default": 0.0,
                            "description": "Height above the surface at which the base-state temperature, pressure and density profiles are evaluated."
                        },
                        "T_bar": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "K",
                            "description": "Base-state temperature T̄(z) = Θ·(1 − z/H_s) (Eq. 2.7) — linear in height, reaching absolute zero at z = H_s."
                        },
                        "p_bar": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "Pa",
                            "description": "Base-state pressure p̄(z) = P_0·(1 − z/H_s)^(C_p/R_d) (Eq. 2.8), the hydrostatically balanced profile of the isentropic atmosphere."
                        },
                        "ρ_bar": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "kg/m^3",
                            "description": "Base-state density ρ̄(z) = P_0/(R_d·Θ)·(1 − z/H_s)^(C_p/R_d − 1) (Eq. 2.9), from the ideal-gas law applied to the isentropic profile."
                        },
                        "H_s": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m",
                            "description": "Isentropic scale height H_s = c_p·Θ/g — the depth over which the linear base-state temperature profile would fall to absolute zero."
                        }
                    },
                    "equations": [
                        {
                            "_comment": "Isentropic scale height H_s = c_p·Θ/g — Clark (1977) Section 2; the linear depth scale of the isentropic base state.",
                            "lhs": "H_s",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "/",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "*",
                                        "args": [
                                            "c_p",
                                            "Θ"
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    "g"
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "_comment": "Eq. 2.7 — base-state temperature T̄(z) = Θ·(1 − z/H_s), linear in height above the surface.",
                            "lhs": "T_bar",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "Θ",
                                    {
                                        "op": "+",
                                        "args": [
                                            1,
                                            {
                                                "op": "*",
                                                "args": [
                                                    -1,
                                                    {
                                                        "op": "/",
                                                        "args": [
                                                            "z",
                                                            "H_s"
                                                        ]
                                                    }
                                                ]
                                            }
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "_comment": "Eq. 2.8 — base-state pressure p̄(z) = P_0·(1 − z/H_s)^(C_p/R_d).",
                            "lhs": "p_bar",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "P_0",
                                    {
                                        "op": "^",
                                        "args": [
                                            {
                                                "op": "+",
                                                "args": [
                                                    1,
                                                    {
                                                        "op": "*",
                                                        "args": [
                                                            -1,
                                                            {
                                                                "op": "/",
                                                                "args": [
                                                                    "z",
                                                                    "H_s"
                                                                ]
                                                            }
                                                        ]
                                                    }
                                                ]
                                            },
                                            "inv_kappa"
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "_comment": "Eq. 2.9 — base-state density ρ̄(z) = P_0/(R_d·Θ)·(1 − z/H_s)^(C_p/R_d − 1).",
                            "lhs": "ρ_bar",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            "P_0",
                                            {
                                                "op": "*",
                                                "args": [
                                                    "R_d",
                                                    "Θ"
                                                ]
                                            }
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "op": "^",
                                        "args": [
                                            {
                                                "op": "+",
                                                "args": [
                                                    1,
                                                    {
                                                        "op": "*",
                                                        "args": [
                                                            -1,
                                                            {
                                                                "op": "/",
                                                                "args": [
                                                                    "z",
                                                                    "H_s"
                                                                ]
                                                            }
                                                        ]
                                                    }
                                                ]
                                            },
                                            "inv_kappa_m1"
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
